e shows the close interconnection of spheres we take as discrete: public and private, family and outsiders, work and leisure. Combining archaeological evidence with Roman texts and comparative material from other cultures, Wallace-Hadrill raises a range of new questions. How did the organization of space and the use of decoration help to structure social encounters between owner and visitor, man and woman, master and slave? What sort of "households" did the inhabitants of the Roman house form? How did the world of work relate to that of entertainment and leisure? How widely did the luxuries of the rich spread among the houses of craftsmen and shopkeepers? Through analysis of the remains of over two hundred houses, Wallace-Hadrill reveals the remarkably dynamic social environment of early imperial Italy, and the vital part that houses came to play in defining what it meant "to live as a Roman."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh  aAbdication.  aAedicula.  aAlleius Nigidius Maius.  aAllusion.  aAncillae.  aAntechamber.  aApartment.  aArchetype.  aArchitectural plan.  aAristocracy.  aArt group.  aAuthor.  aBiography.  aBuilding.  aCabinetry.  aCity-state.  aCivil society.  aClothing.  aCommius.  aConsideration.  aContemporary society.  aCount.  aCredential.  aCultural capital.  aCultural history.  aDesigner.  aDowry.  aDwelling.  aDynasty.  aEconomy.  aEdward Gorey.  aEphesus.  aEtiquette.  aExedra.  aExtended family.  aFloriculture.  aFreedman.  aHerculaneum.  aHouse plan.  aHouse.  aHousehold.  aHousing.  aInfrastructure.  aInsula (building).  aInterior design.  aLegatee.  aLiterature.  aLiving Space.  aLodging.  aMagnificence (history of ideas).  aMattress.  aNobility.  aOccup